<table class="border" cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%" align="center">
<tr>
	<td class="thead" style="font-weight:normal" >		
			<!-- status icon and date -->
			<a name="post22583"><img class="inlineimg" src="http://www.thesteelwarrior.org/forum/images/tren_z/statusicon/post_old.gif" alt="Old" border="0" /></a>
			
				07-09-2003
			
			
			<!-- / status icon and date -->				
	</td>
	<td class="thead" style="font-weight:normal" align="right">
		&nbsp;
		#<a href="showpost.php?s=1a85ad6785bc6649c5de13714abee020&amp;p=22583&amp;postcount=9" target="new"><strong>9</strong></a>
	</td>
</tr>
<tr valign="top">
	<td class="alt2" style="border-right: 1px solid #181B16;"  width="160">
		<div id="postmenu_22583">
				
				<a class="bigusername" href="member.php?s=1a85ad6785bc6649c5de13714abee020&amp;u=254"><div style="font-size:14pt; width:140px;"> Brokkah Narrow</div></a>
				<script type="text/javascript"> vbmenu_register("postmenu_22583", true); </script>
				
			</div>
			
		    <div class="smallfont">Registered User</div>
			
		
			
				<div class="smallfont">
					&nbsp;<br /><a href="member.php?s=1a85ad6785bc6649c5de13714abee020&amp;u=254"><img src="images/avatars/0/441.gif" alt="Brokkah Narrow's Avatar" border="0" /></a>
				</div>
			
			
					<div class="smallfont">
				&nbsp;<br />
				<div class="info"><span class="smallfont">

Offline:





</span> </div>
				<div class="info">Join Date: Apr 2003</div>
				<div class="info">Location: Rivervale</div>
				<div class="info">Guild: <a href="www.aurorapolaris.com">Aurora Polaris</a></div>
				<div class="info">Server: <a href="pub13.ezboard.com/btunare">Tunare</a></div>
				<div class="info"><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=68253&resize=true" target=_blank">Magelo Link</a></div>
				 
				<div class="info">Posts: 156 
				</div>
				<div class="info">   </div>
				</div>														
		
	</td>
	<td class="alt1">
	
		
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div>This problem got so badly on my nerves I wrote a post for our guild tactics forum. Its been stickied ever since, hope it of use to you:-<br />
<br />
---------------------------<br />
<br />
This is not a rant. It is a 'How to' guide on mob positioning and aggro management. Newer members with less raiding experience may not be aware of some of the points raised here, I urge them to read and digest what I have written. There may also be some points raised that even our more experienced members were not aware of. Similarly if you can see I have missed something or made an error, please let me know and I will add/amend where appropriate. <br />
<br />
<br />
We seem to be having some problems with these areas at the moment, and since as we progress through PoP they will become more and more important I thought it was time we broke it down and worked out exactly what everyone's responsibility in these 2 areas is. As a Main Tank, I get to experience the problems with these two areas every day, and they are the 2 things that give me the biggest headaches and cause me to rant in raid channel. We must start improving our raid discipline or we will face severe problems later on. This article relates to boss mob encounters, not exp groups or trash clearing although there are area of discipline that cross over. <br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
1) Mob Positioning <br />
<br />
What are the types of positioning required? <br />
<br />
i) Pin/Cornering - Vindi style fight. Everyone on the mobs back, MT in the corner. You can disregard everything said below if we are cornering as positioning is fixed. <br />
<br />
ii) Wall pin - Aaryonar style fight. Mob body is in the wall, head sticking outwards. Melee balance on either side to pin it in place. Positioning very important, melee must be constantly aware of mob drift. <br />
<br />
iii) Wall Walk - Dagarn style fight. Everyone on the mobs back and sides. MT walks the mob up and down a wall, calling swithces. Positioning not too important here, although all melee directly on the mobs back means more switches, which means a reduction in dps. Attacking from the back left/right quarter allows you to still avoid the mobs defensive skills whilst helping to reduce the speed of push. <br />
<br />
iv) Standard Walk - Eashen style fight. Everyone on the mobs back. Positioning quite important to avoid lateral drift. Melee must spread evenly across the mobs back, allowing the MT to walk in a straight line back and forth calling switches when needed. If you see the mob drifting laterally, attack off, reposition yourself to counter, carry on. <br />
<br />
v) Circle Walk - BoT Fire Tower style fight. Everyone on the mobs back. MT will spin/walk in a circle, positioning fairly important to avoid drift into walls or caster area. Pets especially need to be managed carefully. <br />
<br />
vi) Mob in place, non-rooted - Auliffe/Cursed style fight. Mob must be kept static. positioning is VITAL in these fights. Melee and pets must constantly reposition themselves to ensure the mob is not drifting. MT can reposition slightly but generally this tactic is used where space is at a premium and drift cannot be allowed to happen. <br />
<br />
Why is mob positioning important? <br />
<br />
i) To avoid harmful AE <br />
ii) To allow line of sight damage dealers to do their job (Mage, Ranger) <br />
iii) To allow rogues to Backstab <br />
iv) To keep main tank/raid in range of healing classes and nukers. <br />
v) To allow melee to maximise their dps. <br />
vi) To prevent corpse being unreachable to loot <br />
<br />
What are the limits on a MT's ability to control positioning? <br />
<br />
Your MT can control the direction the mob faces, thats all. He has no control over lateral push(strafe), speed of vertical push and to a lesser extent wheeling of the mob (ie where it seems to be pushed around in a circle). Also his level of aggro limits the amount of re-positioning he can do by summon/back up or straight moving. <br />
<br />
What factors effect mob position? <br />
<br />
i) Pets - Pet push is one of the biggest factors in positioning. In order from most push to least my experience shows that pets push in this order - Beastlord, Mage, Shaman, Necro, Enc Charmed pet. Others do not do enough damage to warrant mentioning. It is the pet caster's responsibility to ensure their pet is providing a balanced push on the mob. Be proactive about this, if you can see a mob drifting and your pet is contributing to that drift then back it off and move it to counter the push. Ideally before the fight starts, pets should be positioned evenly around the mob to minimize their push. The only exception to this is where we pin (or corner) a mob, in which case stick em all on its back. On a mob where we do not corner it NEVER EVER USE YOUR SWARM PETS. Seriously, the dps increase from it is not worth the insane push these pets can generate. <br />
<br />
ii) Melee - Melee damage contributes to mob push. It does it in a couple of ways - straight melee and special attacks. Straight melee weapons push in this order, most to least push - Blunt, Slashing Piercing. Blunt weapons can push a lot. Piercing weapons hardly push at all. Special attacks such as kick, bash, slam and monk flying kick all push more than normal melee. This can be used to your advantage in 'counter-push' situations. It is melee's responsibility to balance themselves around the mob they are attacking. Do not all stand in a clump, arrange yourselves so push is spread as evenly as possible. This will help prevent wheeling and lateral drift. MAX MELEE RANGE. There is a reason this gets screamed every raid. The further away from the mob you are, the less effect your melee has on push. It also helps with aggro management but I will discuss that later on. Finally max melee range will allow you to avoid some AE effects that you would otherwise catch, and if(when) we get to the elemental planes there are mobs who AE RAMPAGE for quad 2-3k damage. You need to be at max melee range to avoid it, so now is a good time to start practising. <br />
<br />
iii) Spells - Direct Damage and stun spells probably contribute the least to mob push due to virtually all bosses being immune to stun. However, spells with a knockback component can still move a mob. Again, try to not bunch up and all cast along the same axis, as this will just push the mob along faster. <br />
<br />
What do I do when positioning starts to break down? <br />
<br />
STOP ATTACKING <br />
BACK PETS OFF <br />
<br />
These 2 things should be done immediately it becomes apparent mob positioning has broken down. This will give your MT a chance to re-align himself. Now get back into position and start attacking again on the MTs call, arranged logically to push the mob in the desired direction using the suggestions raised above. <br />
<br />
Listen to your MT. He is controlling the direction of the fight, if he needs melee to move then do it. If he needs pets moving then do it. If he asks you to stop attacking then for gods sake DO IT. We dont shout and scream for our own amusement, it is to ensure mob slaying goes as smoothly and efficiently as possibl <br />
<br />
If in this situation you have aggro, try to move as close to the MT's position as you can. <br />
<br />
Can I help 'counter-push'? <br />
<br />
Be aware during fights. Experienced players will know roughly where a mob should be positioned during that fight. If you can see it start to drift then by all means move to counter it. On cursed for example, melee are constantly moving to balance the mob in an area roughly 5 foot square. The same tactic we use there will work on a larger scale if you think intelligently about the direction the mob is moving, and what you can do to counter this. <br />
<br />
2) Aggro Management <br />
<br />
What is aggro management, and why do i need it? <br />
<br />
Aggro management is the process by which you ensure aggro remains on the main tank, and away from you. It is necessary in raid situations to allow the healing power to focus on 1 person, and keep the mob pointing in 1 direction. This allows the rest of the raid to do maximum dps with the minimum of risk. <br />
<br />
Warriors generally tank boss mobs due to 1 discipline, defensive. This allows us to cut melee damage taken to as much as half, but has the side effect of reducing our own damage output by 35%. This makes us increasingly reliant on procs for aggro, and also the 'hit and hope' taunt button. Additionally some warriors will have the area taunt skill which has a side effect of being a 100% successful taunt button. Unfortunately it is on a 15 minute timer, so normally is not available more than once a fight. <br />
<br />
These are the limits imposed on warriors, it is your job to work within the confines of them. If the warrior loses aggro once its established, its not his fault, its yours. <br />
<br />
How do I manage my aggro? <br />
<br />
All - <br />
<br />
WAIT FOR ASSIST. The main tank waits to call assist for a reason. It is to give the debuffers time to debuff, heal chain to settle and to ensure he has sufficient aggro to keep the mob on him for as long as possible. I dont care if you have a method for reducing your aggro, there is absolutely NO excuse for attacking a mob before the MT calls assist. You arent helping him, and potentially you will screw his aggro generation up. <br />
<br />
Do NOT sit on inc, or for the first few seconds of the fight. You are asking to get splattered. <br />
<br />
Keep above frenzy HP levels. Nothing a warrior can do including AE taunt will override frenzy aggro due to low HP. It is your responsibility to get out of AE range, get a heal, or both. <br />
<br />
On a tank switch - STOP ATTACK, CALL PETS OFF. Let the new tank regain aggro, he will call assist again when ready. Treat a tank switch as effectively the start of a new fight and you shouldnt go wrong. <br />
<br />
Melee - <br />
<br />
Cycle attacks. Your dps will massively overhaul the main tanks via pure melee. Just turning attack off for 1 round every 15 seconds or so will help him. <br />
<br />
Put your aggro proc weapons away. Any weapon proccing slow, root, stun, knockback, rune or pure aggro should be bagged or at the very least off-handed. <br />
<br />
MAX MELEE RANGE. A lot of mobs aggro is based at least partially on proximity. The further you are away from the mob, the less chance you have of getting unwanted aggro. <br />
<br />
Use your aggro reducing skills. Monks and SKs should FD, it has a fixed aggro reducing component (go to monkly-business and check if you dont believe me). Rogues evade, rangers jolt if it can stick. <br />
<br />
Hybrids, dont use aggro spells such as stun, snare, slow, ranger imbues with stun component. There is 1 situation this is acceptable and thats where you are the puller. In that case, go to town and transfer the aggro to warrior via AE taunt. <br />
<br />
Casters - <br />
<br />
Time your nukes/dots. Dont start chain casting your biggest DD from the word go. Start slow, and build it up towards the end. There is no way any Damage caster should be getting aggro from a warrior on a raid. <br />
<br />
Use your aggro reducers. Boggle, Concussion, Spell casting Subtlety, the tash aggro reducing thing from PoI. All are gonna help. <br />
<br />
<br />
If we can all start to use a bit of common sense and discipline, raid targets will be a lot easier to handle.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		<!-- sig -->
			<div>
				__________________<br />
